**Server returns plain text with 200:**

```js
$.ajax({
    url: "/some-api",
    type: "POST",
    dataType: "json",
    success: function (data) {
        console.log("success:", data);   // ← NEVER runs
    },
    error: function (xhr) {
        console.log("error:", xhr.status, xhr.responseText);  // ← RUNS
        // prints: error: 200 No data received from service
    }
});
```

Response from server:
```
HTTP 200 OK
Body: "No data received from service"
```

jQuery tries to do `JSON.parse("No data received from service")` → throws `SyntaxError` → routes to `error`.

---

**Server returns valid JSON with 200:**

```js
$.ajax({
    url: "/some-api",
    type: "POST",
    dataType: "json",
    success: function (data) {
        console.log("success:", data);   // ← RUNS
        // prints: success: { status: "ok" }
    },
    error: function (xhr) {
        console.log("error:", xhr.status);  // ← NEVER runs
    }
});
```

Response from server:
```
HTTP 200 OK
Body: {"status": "ok"}
```

jQuery does `JSON.parse('{"status":"ok"}')` → succeeds → routes to `success`.

---

**The rule:**

| HTTP Status | Response Body | Callback |
|---|---|---|
| 200 | valid JSON | `success` |
| 200 | plain text / empty | `error` |
| 404 / 500 | anything | `error` |

**Scenario: User clicks "Save Address" on a checkout page**

```js
$jq("#save-address-btn").on("click", function () {

    $jq.ajax({
        url: "/api/user/save-address",
        type: "POST",
        data: JSON.stringify({ street: "123 Main St", city: "Singapore" }),
        contentType: "application/json",
        dataType: "json",
        success: function (response) {
            // redirect to payment page
            window.location.href = "/checkout/payment";
        },
        error: function (xhr) {
            alert("Something went wrong. Please try again.");
        }
    });
});
```

**On production** — server returns:
```
HTTP 200 OK
Body: {"saved": true, "addressId": "ADR-9912"}
```
→ `success` fires → user goes to payment page. Works fine.

---

**On staging** — backend team deployed a new build, the save-address endpoint is temporarily broken and returns:
```
HTTP 200 OK
Body: "Address service unavailable"
```
→ jQuery tries `JSON.parse("Address service unavailable")` → fails → `error` fires → user sees *"Something went wrong"* alert

---

**The confusing part for the developer:**

They check the Network tab → see **200 OK** → think *"the request succeeded, why is the error showing?"*

Then they click the Response tab → see plain text instead of JSON → check the code → spot `dataType: "json"` → realize jQuery is failing on the parse step, not the HTTP step.

That's exactly what happened in your preferences.js — the API on local returns `"No data received from service"` instead of JSON, so jQuery always routes to `error` even though the HTTP status is 200.

Yes, exactly.

The backend code is probably something like:

```java
if (data == null || data.isEmpty()) {
    response.getWriter().write("No data received from service");
    return;
}

// normal flow
response.getWriter().write(gson.toJson(result));
```

So when your local environment has no data (no real user session, no connection to the actual database/service), it hits that condition and returns the plain text message instead of JSON.

The API is saying: *"I got your request but I have nothing to give back."*

On a real environment with a proper logged-in user and live backend services, it would return actual JSON data — and jQuery's `success` would fire normally.

